ğŸŒŸ Day 60: GFG160 Challenge ğŸŒŸ

ğŸ”— Problem: Container With Most Water

ğŸ’¡ Approach:
1ï¸âƒ£ Two Pointers: Start with left at 0 and right at n-1.
2ï¸âƒ£ Calculate Water: Use min(arr[left], arr[right]) * (right - left).
3ï¸âƒ£ Move the Shorter Line:
ğŸ”¹ If arr[left] < arr[right], move left forward.
ğŸ”¹ Else, move right backward.
4ï¸âƒ£ Track Maximum Water: Repeat until left < right.

â³ Complexity:
Time: ğ‘‚(ğ‘›)
Space: ğ‘‚(1)

âœ… Efficiently found the max water a container can store! ğŸš€


// C++ Program to find the maximum amount of water in the 
// container using Two Pointer Technique

#include <vector>
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int maxWater(vector<int> &arr) {
      int left = 0, right = arr.size() - 1;
    int res = 0;
    while(left < right) {
        
        // Find the water stored in the container between 
        // arr[left] and arr[right]
        int water = min(arr[left], arr[right]) * (right - left);
        res = max(res, water);
      
        if(arr[left] < arr[right])
            left += 1;
        else
            right -= 1;
    }
  
    return res;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {2, 1, 8, 6, 4, 6, 5, 5};
    cout << maxWater(arr);
}
